	axonal injury. (2) Magnetic resonance spectroscopy acquires metabolite
	information reflecting neuronal integrity and function from multiple
	brain regions and provides sensitive, noninvasive assessment of neurochemical
	alterations that offers early prognostic information regarding the
	outcome. (3) Diffusion weighted imaging is based on differences in
	diffusion of water molecules within the brain and has been shown
	to be very sensitive in the early detection of ischemic injury. It
	is now being used to study the direct effects of traumatic injury
	as well as those due to secondary ischemia. (4) Diffusion tensor
	imaging is a form of diffusion weighted imaging and allows better
	evaluation of white matter fiber tracts by taking advantage of the
	intrinsic directionality (anisotropy) of water diffusion in human
